{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584401"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:45:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:45:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14467"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14467"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.22,0.39,0.22,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7162"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114030"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7162"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14467"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96044"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4905"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17131"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17818"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114030","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114030"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following vessel types contains the majority of the body\u0027s blood volume at rest?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Systemic arteries","Capillaries","Large veins","Small veins and venules","Arterioles"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAt rest, the majority of the body\u0027s blood volume (approximately 60-70%) is contained within the \u003Cstrong\u003Esmall veins and venules\u003C/strong\u003E. These vessels have high capacitance and compliance, allowing them to accommodate large volumes of blood with relatively little increase in pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic arteries\u003C/strong\u003E contain about 10-15% of the blood volume, while \u003Cstrong\u003Ecapillaries\u003C/strong\u003E hold only about 5%. \u003Cstrong\u003ELarge veins\u003C/strong\u003E contain approximately 15% of the blood volume. \u003Cstrong\u003EArterioles\u003C/strong\u003E, despite their important role in regulating blood flow, contain only a small percentage of the total blood volume.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis distribution of blood volume is important for several reasons: it provides a reservoir of blood that can be mobilised during times of increased demand, such as exercise or blood loss; it helps maintain venous return to the heart, which is crucial for cardiac output; and the high compliance of veins allows for accommodation of changes in blood volume without significant changes in blood pressure. Understanding this distribution is essential for comprehending cardiovascular physiology and the body\u0027s response to various physiological and pathological conditions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["At rest, the majority of the body\u0027s blood volume (approximately 60-70%) is contained within the small veins and venules.","The distribution of blood volume in the circulatory system reflects the capacitance and compliance of different vessel types."],"references":["Magder S. Mechanical Limits of Cardiac Output at Maximal Aerobic Exercise [Internet]. Exercise Physiology. IntechOpen; 2022. Available from: http://dx.doi.org/10.5772/intechopen.103908","Zivadinov R, Chung CP. Potential involvement of the extracranial venous system in central nervous system disorders and aging. BMC Med. 2013 Dec 17;11:260. doi: 10.1186/1741-7015-11-260. PMID: 24344742; PMCID: PMC3866257.","Gopalan, C., \u0026 Kirk, E. Biology of Cardiovascular and Metabolic Diseases. 2022. Academic Press","Hemmings, H. C., \u0026 Egan, T. D. Pharmacology and physiology for anesthesia e-book: foundations and clinical application. 2012. Elsevier Health Sciences","Magder S. Blood pressure regulation. In: Cannesson M, Pearse R, eds. Perioperative Hemodynamic Monitoring and Goal Directed Therapy: From Theory to Practice. Cambridge University Press; 2014:47-55. Available from: https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/abs/perioperative-hemodynamic-monitoring-and-goal-directed-therapy/blood-pressure-regulation/82EFE91BCB092B34F337BD3C583F9476"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96044"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14467"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96044","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96044"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T19:38:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T19:39:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7162"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114030"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta"